Mr. May has a very strong infantry combat background as he was a squad leader during Operation: Moshtarak and was tasked with controlling key parts of the city, training the soldiers of the Afghanistan National Army and Afghanistan National Police, as well as fighting against a well-trained enemy in their own back yard. His expertise in this area gives him the ability to easily translate and teach his skills to a wide range of people. Any assistant instructors that may be used are hand selected by Chris May and will have an equal combat background. title: For Sale/Trade:  1842 Soldier Marked Rifle Musket!
postcontent:
Up for sale is a very unique and great Civil War militaria piece. Overall the metal shows armory bright, as is correct, the lock plate having clear Springfield 1853 marks at rear and the Springfield eagle/US forward. Lock plate and hammer are smooth with smokey gray over silver. The barrel is generally a tad lighter silver/gray with an overlay of that powdery dark gray tiny dimpling from exposure and use, but with clear V/P/eagle proofs and clear 1854 date on the breechplug tang. The mismatched dates are TOTALLY CORRECT on a "rifled and sighted" model 1842. The guns were disassembled and the parts sorted without regard to which gun they came off of.
What makes this musket so interesting are the added markings put on by the soldier. Four small circles have been stamped around a central oval just forward of the bolster on the top of their barrel. This may be a rough representation of a Catholic symbol based on Jesus in a central circle surrounded by four other circles containing crosses and two human figures in each. Further evidence of religious symbolism is a clearly carved Christian cross on the left side flat, This cross has a Celtic flavor with half a circle incised above the cross arms. The traditional Celtic cross bears a complete circle, but this seems very close. The initials “GS” and “GHS” next to a “50 M..” have been deeply carved on the underside near the triggerguard, another “G” to rear of the lock.Best research narrows this down to either Massachusetts or Missouri (only two "M" states with at least 50 regiments of infantry). The likely owner in my opinion is George H. Spofford a 28 year old shoe cutter from Georgetown, Mass. He enlisted in the 50th Mass 9/19/62 and served his entire term of service until 8/24/63 when the entire regiment was mustered out of service. He then rejoined the 17th Unattached Company of infantry and served again from late 1864 through June of 1865. I believe the Catholic and Celtic symbols on the gun are more likely done by someone from the densely Catholic state of Massachusetts...
Asking $1500, or will trade for a M1917 revolver. This is your rare chance to have a Civil War musket with provenance. Additional pictures available upon request. Period-correct bayonet included.

title: For Sale:  Harrington and Richardson M1 Garand H&R M1 Garand Nice Wood
postcontent: The rifle is a U.S. M1 (Garand) chambered for the .30-06 cartridge. Overall appearance and condition is good. The rear receiver is marked H&R ARMS CO with a serial number of 5683947. The receiver markings place this rifle into the second block of numbers alotted for Harrington & Richardson Arms Company. H&R produced this pattern to supplement existing supplies of M1s during the Korean War. Examples manufactured in this later block (to include those made by International Harvester and higher-number Springfields) do not generally command the prices of pre- and World War II-era rifles. In addition to the clarity of stamps and markings on steel parts, the lack of arsenal marks suggest that the receiver/barrel assembly retains the original finish. Wear is commensurate to that of a rifle 70+ years old. Some small parts appear to be of earlier vintage. The intact nature of the drawing numbers on the right-front receiver leg indicate that this rifle was never cut. The stock is a mismatch. Per the markings and inspecting agent's initials this dates to a Springfield Armory example produced between November 1944 and June 1945. Three of four cartouches are present. Those remaining are faint, and the lack of corresponding arsenal marks suggest that any refinish work was done outside of government supervision. Overall, the rifle appears to be a good example of a post-Korean M1 which has been restocked and rebuilt with mismatched smaller components. An M1 in this configuration has more appeal as a well-dressed shooter than a collector's piece. Comes with one bandelier with 6 clips of M2 ball ammo, and 6 additional clips.
